Right now, the simplest way to run the workflow is to treat it as a local prompt-and-script pipeline.

What you have

You now effectively have:

generator prompts (generation/v1, v2, v3)

evaluator prompts (evaluation/)

Python scripts (scripts/)

gold-standard test cases (gold_standard/)


So “running the workflow” means one of three things:

1. Run one study design case through the evaluator


2. Run a batch of cases


3. Run an A/B test of prompt versions




---

1. Minimum viable way to run it now

Step 1: Put the repo on your machine

Your repo should look roughly like:

clinical_ai_prompts/
├── generation/
├── evaluation/
├── scripts/
├── gold_standard/

Step 2: Make sure Python is installed

In VS Code terminal or command line:

python --version

or on some systems:

python3 --version

Step 3: Save the scripts

Make sure these files exist:

scripts/csr_study_design_evaluation.py

scripts/batch_evaluate.py

scripts/ab_test_generator_prompts.py


And the prompt files exist in the right places.


---

2. How to run a single evaluation

This is the easiest starting point.

Step 1: Go into the repo folder

cd clinical_ai_prompts

Step 2: Run the evaluation harness

If your script has the demo block at the bottom, run:

python scripts/csr_study_design_evaluation.py

If your system uses python3:

python3 scripts/csr_study_design_evaluation.py

What happens

It will:

load the scorer prompts

create a sample workflow input

call the dummy client

print a summary

save JSON output


Expected output file:

evaluation_outputs/sample_workflow_evaluation.json

Important note

As written, this only works as a wiring test because it uses DummyLLMClient.

That means:

the script structure runs

the JSON parsing runs

the outputs save correctly


But it is not yet calling a real model.


---

3. What you need to do to make it real

You need to replace DummyLLMClient with your real model call.

That means editing this part:

class DummyLLMClient:
    def generate(self, prompt: str) -> str:
        ...

and replacing it with something that actually sends the prompt to the model you want to use.

Conceptually:

class RealLLMClient:
    def generate(self, prompt: str) -> str:
        # send prompt to model
        # return model text output
        return response_text

So the workflow is already structured, but the model connection layer still needs to be plugged in.


